    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Defending Napster To the Editor:</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Thomas Wolfe letter on Aug 31 article holds both sides in debate over Napster neglect benefits of innovation and progress likely to sprout if Napster were left alone; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Re ''Taking Sides in the Napster War'' (Aug. 31): Both sides in the debate over Napster glaringly neglect the benefits of innovation and progress that would be likely to sprout if Napster was left alone. If we submit to the argument of the few -- musicians and record companies -- we ignore the possibility of long-term benefits for the many. By doing so, we would be neglecting the oft-repeated lessons of history. Once the artists and record companies open their minds and embrace the inevitable, I am certain that they will find new streams of revenue, as always.</p>
        <p>THOMAS WOLFE  Bronxville, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
